entry.title: [Reland] WebUI: Patch Lit to use 'lit-html-desktop' trusted types policy.
entry.content:
Reland notes: Updated ash::EnableTrustedTypesCSP() to include the new

TrustedTypes policy for Desktop's Lit bundle. The breakage was missed

because the relevant test only runs on dbg builds at the moment.



Renaming Desktop's Lit bundle trusted type policy from 'lit-html' to

'lit-html-desktop', because some CrOS UIs already use a separate

CrOS-only Lit bundle served from [1], which when used at the same time

as Desktop's Lit bundle served from [2] results in a runtime error as

follows:



Uncaught TypeError: Failed to execute 'createPolicy' on

'TrustedTypePolicyFactory': Policy with name "lit-html" already exists."



By renaming Desktop's trusted type policy, using both Lit bundle's at

the same time is possible, which will be necessary for CrOS UIs that

depend on both cr_elements and third_party/material_web_components.



Also moving all third_party/node/ patch files to a dedicated folder

as a cleanup, since there are now 5 such files.



[1] chrome://resources/mwc/lit/index.js

[2] chrome://resources/lit/v3_0/lit.rollup.js

entry.title: [Read Aloud] Fix previous navigation.
entry.content:
This is a basic implementation that just stores the previous lists of

nodes returned by #GetNextText and uses those when navigating previous / back.



This prevents us from repeatedly recalcuating and refinding sentence

bounds, and this will also be robust against any modifications and

improvements to using AXPosition with #GetNextText.



In the future, we will still need to be able to determine

previous nodes in a #GetPreviousNodes method as a reverse of

what #GetNextNodes currently does e.g. if granularity switches

in the middle of speech or we jump to a different node.



However, I'm in favor of the approach in this CL for now because:

1.) We will still be able to benefit from storing processed nodes after logic has been

added for reversing from an arbitrary node in cases with

simple forward / back navigation.



2.) I anticipate a few more changes to #GetNextNodes before any

changes need to be made to previous navigation,

so this prevents us from duplicating work in the meantime.



3.) We're still a bit away from features that would need a #GetPreviousNodes method.



4.) I initially looked into using AXPosition#CreatePreviousSentenceStartPosition

and got some unexpected results, so I think it will take more time to

debug, so this CL unblocks other work like highlighting, dependent on

previous / next.

entry.title: Notify the flow thread about style change for inlines as well.
entry.content:
We only did it for LayoutBox or better, but this is necessary for

LayoutInline as well.



When a layout object changes whether or not it's a containing block for

out-of-flow positioned descendants, the multicol flow thread machinery

may need to insert or remove LayoutMultiColumnSet objects - since

ouf-of-flow positioned descendants may become part of (or cease to be

part of) the multicol container because such a change.



This is detected in NeedsToReinsertIntoFlowThread().



Move the flow thread hooks in StyleWillChange() and StyleDidChange()

from LayoutBox to LayoutBoxModelObject, so that this also works for

inlines.



This was most likely a LayoutNG regression, since the legacy engine

didn't really let inlines act as containing blocks.

entry.title: [a11y] EnableAccessibility should be a no-op if a11y is already enabled.
entry.content:
BrowserAccessibilityStateImpl::EnableAccessibility should not do any

work if a11y is already enabled.



On Mac, accessibilitySetValue can cause us to call EnableAccessibility

multiple times, causing the web contents to churn their tree if a11y

is already enabled. With the "Hover Text" feature on Mac, this caused

us to be constantly giving the feature a new tree, seemingly confusing

it and causing it to not show the text as expected. On larger sites I

was even able to reproduce a hang in some cases due to the size of the

tree being serialized.



This change simply checks to see if a11y is already enabled when

EnableAccessibility is called, and if so, we don't do any additional

work.



Fixed: 1513295

entry.title: Make ComputedStyle subgroups use compressed Members.
entry.content:
As we've optimized ComputedStyle more for Oilpan, and also generally

reduced the number of DataRef operations we need to make (due to memory

optimizations, better use of MPC etc.), we can now use Member<> instead

performance hit. (Performance is even a tiny bit better, although there

entry.title: Clone and update multicol fragments properly when adding OOFs.
entry.content:
If the original inner multicol container had descendant multicols with

pending OOFs, make sure that the cloned and updated multicol also

reflects this state.



For that to work, we also need to allow more OOF descendant propagation

when cloning and updating fragmentainers via SimplifiedLayoutAlgorithm.

Remove the disable_oof_descendants_propagation_ flag, and instead block

such propagation for OOF fragments that are inside a fragmentainer. Such

fragments are special, and the propagation is handled manually in

OutOfFlowLayoutPart::AddOOFToFragmentainer(). All other fragments should

propagate normally.



The problem here was that the HasNestedMulticolsWithOOFs() flag in

PhysicalFragment got lost when the fragments got cloned and updated, which in turn prevented us from missing the cache in

LayoutBox::CachedLayoutResult() when re-laying out.

entry.title: [BRP] Fix OOB poison tests
entry.content:
Several tests would fail when backup_ref_ptr_poison_oob_ptr is true.



Other than the obvious AllowPtrArithmetic, there were a couple less

trivial issues:

- raw_ptr needs to be zero'ed or destructed before freeing memory to

avoid triggering Dangling Pointer Detector

- CountingRawPtr is no longer backed by BRP implementation, so OOB

protection won't kick in

- A bug in BackupRefPtrTest.Advance has been fixed to correctly test

larger sizes, so a hardcoded array no longer cuts it

- volatile is needed to avoid optimizing out dereferences (std::ignore

is enough if the code triggers CHECK)

entry.title: [Office upload] Handle escape key as a "cancel" in File Handler dialog
entry.content:
Handle the escape keydown event as a "cancel" user choice in the File

Handler dialog.



Previously, an escape keydown event would close all office upload

dialogs, except for the OneDrive setup dialog, with an empty user choice

since CloudUploadDialog::ShouldCloseDialogOnEscape() was true.



This led to weird metric results as an empty user choice (which is never

expected) would be recorded and mistakenly translated to the user

choosing an invalid local file task.



Update the code so that an escape in the File Handler dialog will

correctly be recorded as a "cancel" user choice.



Add keydown event listeners on the document in connectedCallback() and

explicitly remove them in disconnectedCallback(). They have to be

removed as otherwise they will be called upon keydown events after they

have been removed from the DOM.



Bug: b/315727684
